ce:section.ce:para:
The crystal structures of various PtxMo1-x@graphene nanosponges were verified by their X-ray diffraction (XRD) profiles (Fig. 2
                        a). For all PtxMo1-x@graphene electrocatalysts prepared, the XRD profiles showed diffraction patterns associated with the face-centered-cubic (fcc) Pt structure (JCPDS 04-0802) with three broad peaks at (111), (200), and (311). Peaks corresponding to Mo metal and its oxides did not appear in the XRD results. With each XRD peak, the average crystallite size (L) of the PtxMo1-x nanocrystallites was calculated using the width of the reflection peak according to the Debye–Scherrer equation: L = 0.9λ/(β cos θ), where β is the full-width-at-half-maximum (FWHM) of the peak, θ is the angle of diffraction and λ is the wavelength of the x-ray radiation. Here, the (111) reflection of PtMo nanostructures was used to calculate the average crystallite size according to the Debye–Scherrer formula [27]. The broadening of the peaks is found to increase with an increase in molybdenum concentration. The corresponding average crystallite sizes are 4.29, 4.38, 4.04 and 2.21 nm for Pt90Mo10, Pt75Mo25, Pt50Mo50 , and Pt25Mo75, respectively. Except in the Pt90Mo10 case, the average grain size of PxtMo1-x decreases with an increase in the Mo content. In addition, as the Mo content in the PtMo nanosponges increases, the main peaks slightly shift toward a high angle (the (111) peak in Fig. 2a and Table 1
                        ), indicating an increase in the lattice parameter caused by the replacement of Pt with Mo in the crystal lattice. The lattice parameters determined from the (111) reflection peaks are 3.894, 3.913 and 3.916 Å for Pt75Mo25, Pt50Mo50 and Pt25Mo75, corresponding to d111 spacings of 2.248, 2.259 and 2.261 Å, respectively. The increase in the lattice parameters of the samples is due to the fact that Mo atoms (1.90°A) replace Pt atoms (1.77°A) in the crystallite. The alloy composition controls the value of the lattice parameter, which eventually controls the surface electrocatalytic activity [27].
